and the perfect purgation of sinnes by the bloude of him that only was with out sinne, yet it was not conuenient, that the might of that mercy shoulde worke in this freedome of our willes, with out all peine of the party, or trauell of the offenders. VVhereof mān streight vpon his miserable downe fall (as S. Ambrose excellently well noteth) had warning by the fiery sworde holden at the entraunce of paradise:
